entangled from the many men and women seeking recreation and camaraderie. Following these climbers through time, Joseph Taylor uncovers lessons about the relationship of individuals to groups, sport to society, and nature to culture. He also shows how social and historical contexts influenced adventurers’ choices and experiences, and why some became leading environmental activists—including John Muir, David Brower, and Yvon Chouinard. In a world in which wild nature is increasingly associated with play, and virtuous play with environmental values, Pilgrims of the Vertical explains when and how these ideas developed, and why they became intimately linked to consumerism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aMountaineeringxCaliforniaxYosemite Valley. 0aMountaineeringxEnvironmental aspectsxCaliforniaxYosemite Valley. 0aMountaineeringxEnvironmental aspectszCaliforniazYosemite Valley. 0aMountaineeringzCaliforniazYosemite Valley. 0aRock climbingxCaliforniaxYosemite Valley. 0aRock climbingxEnvironmental aspectsxCaliforniaxYosemite Valley. 0aRock climbingxEnvironmental aspectszCaliforniazYosemite Valley. 0aRock climbingzCaliforniazYosemite Valley. 7aSPORTS & RECREATION / Mountaineering.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z978311044221208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674058606?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674058606423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674058606/original  a978-3-11-044220-5  Harvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-044221-2  HUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999c1893d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aE